<DOC><DOCNO> AP890508-0173 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-89 2056EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-US-Ambassadors     05-08 0213</FIRST><SECOND>AM-US-Ambassadors,220</SECOND><HEAD>Envoys Testify They'll be Alert to European Arms Exports</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush's ambassadors-designate toFrance, Italy and Sweden assured senators Monday they will keepalert to arms sales from those European countries to the ThirdWorld.   The United States has been concerned about the supply of weaponsto developing countries, prompting questions at the Senate ForeignRelations Committe's hearing on the nominations of Walter J.P.Curley as ambassador to France, Charles E. Redman to Sweden andPeter Secchia to Italy.   Redman said the Swedish record is overall a good one and Swedentries to avoid sending arms into areas of tension and conflict.   The Italian government has committed itself to tighteningrestrictions on arms exports, Sechhia said.   Curley said France, a big arms exporter, has a specialrelationship with Iraq and its control over and monitoring ofweapon supplies to French-speaking African countries has been``quite tight.''   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the panel, said heintends to move quickly on the nominations of Secchia and Curley sothat they can be in their new posts when Bush visits Europe laterthis month.   The committee will likely report the three nominations to theSenate floor Wednesday, he said, with action probable by the end ofthis week.</TEXT></DOC>